1. str.split("")
String str = "abc";
String[] arr = str.split("");
Returns: String[] → ["a", "b", "c"]

List<String> list = Arrays.asList(str.split(""));
✅ Works as expected → ["a", "b", "c"]

2. str.toCharArray()
char[] arr = str.toCharArray();
Returns: char[] → ['a', 'b', 'c'] (primitive array)

List<char[]> list = Arrays.asList(str.toCharArray());
⚠️ Gives:
[['a','b','c']]    --> A list with ONE element (the whole array), not individual characters.

💥 Why this happens

Arrays.asList() works like this:
For object arrays (T[]) → converts elements into a list ✅
For primitive arrays (char[], int[]) → treats the entire array as a single object ❌

Because primitives are not objects, Java doesn’t auto-split them.